{"title_page": "John Curr", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n'''John Curr''' (c. 1756 \u2013 27 January 1823) was the manager or [[colliery viewer|viewer]] of the [[Duke of Norfolk]]'s [[collieries]] in [[Sheffield]], England from 1781 to 1801. During this time he made a number of innovations that contributed significantly to the development of the coal mining industry and railways.<ref>Alexander Lock, 'Curr, John (1756\u20131823)', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, September 2015)</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCurr was born in [[County Durham]], England in around 1756.<ref name=\"Day184\">{{Harvnb|Day|McNeil|1996|p=184}}</ref> He was raised and remained a Catholic throughout his life. He moved to Sheffield some time before 1776. In 1780 he was appointed superintendent of the Duke of Norfolk's Sheffield collieries.<ref name=\"Day184\" /> He married Hannah Wilson (18 May 1759 \u2013 10 June 1851<ref>{{cite book|title=Miscellanea IV|year=1907|publisher=Catholic Record Society|page=366}}</ref>) in about 1785, and they had eight children, including [[Joseph Curr]], a Catholic priest, and [[Edward Curr]], who was Secretary of the [[Van Diemen's Land Company]] from 1824 to 1841. He died in Sheffield on 27 January 1823.<ref>{{cite news|title=Births, Deaths, Marriages and Obituaries|newspaper=The Bury and Norwich Post|date=5 February 1823}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nThe career of John Curr has been subject to significant dispute, due to inaccurate statements by early authors about him and misinterpretation.<ref>The historiography of the subject is dealt with at {{Harvnb|Mott|1969|pp=15\u201317 20\u201323}} and {{Harvnb|Lewis|1970|pp= 316\u20139}}.</ref> Older works (such as (or those quoting them) often give the date of his colliery inventions as 1776.<ref>{{Harvnb|Galloway|1898|pp=322\u20134}}</ref> Curr probably came to Sheffield in 1778.  That August, shortly before the expiry of the lease of Sheffield colliery (in Sheffield Park), he wrote a report on it for [[Charles Howard, 10th Duke of Norfolk|the Duke of Norfolk]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Mott|1969|pp=3}}: citing Sheffield Archives, ACM/S217.</ref> Contrary to statements by his son, he was probably not there in 1774, when there were riots against the colliery lessees, who insisted on selling coal only at a yard in Sheffield.<ref>''Universal Magazine'', 2 December 1774: reprinted {{Harvnb|Mott|1969|pp= 16}}.</ref> From Michaelmas 1779, he became superintendent of the Duke's Coal Works.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mott|1969|p= 4}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1787, [[John Buddle, senior]] reported on the transport system introduced by Curr.  He reported Curr's method using L-shaped [[cast iron]] plates cost 6\u00bcd per waggon, whereas the old method cost 10\u00bdd per waggon, a saving of 3\u00bed.  He also referred to Mr Curr's method of 'drawing 2 corves abreast up a shaft 8\u00bd to 9-foot diameter by means of steadying conductors'.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mott|1969|pp= 5}}, citing Sheffield Archives, ACMS223.</ref> Curr substituted small four-wheeled carriages for the sledges that had previously been used to transport coal underground,<ref>{{Harvnb|Galloway|1898|p=322}}</ref> but this meant that underground haulage by boys, rather than ponies.<ref>{{Harvnb|Lewis|1970|p=319}}</ref> The corf wheels and 'roadplates' came from Binks, Booth, and Hartop's nearby Park Ironworks.<ref>{{Harvnb|Lewis|1970|p= 318}} Identification of ironworks from C. Ball et al., ''Water Power on Sheffield Rivers'' (2nd edn, [[South Yorkshire Industrial History Society]], Sheffield, 2006), 192</ref>\n\nThe use of these rails was subsequently promoted by [[Benjamin Outram]] and adopted at many other English mines,<ref name=\"Day184\" /> quarries and ironworks.  In south Wales, railways using his system were known as tramroads (or dramroads).  Today, the term [[plateway]] is sometimes applied to them.\n\n==Patents==\n{|Class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year!!Number!!Subject\n|-\n|1788||1660||For raising coals out of mines using \"conductors\" with tiplers at the surface\n|-\n|1792||1924||For using double ropes\n|-\n|1798||1924||For using flat ropes wound in coils on the winding drum<ref>Mott, 6.</ref>\n|1813|3711|Applying flat ropes to horse-gins\n|-\n| || ||{{Expand list|date=January 2012}}\n|}\n\n== Publications ==\n*{{cite book |last=Curr |first=John |title=The Coal Viewer, and Engine Builder's Practical Companion |year=1797 |publisher=John Northall |location=Sheffield |oclc= 637327681 |ref=harv}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Edward Micklethwaite Curr]], John Curr's grandson\n\n==References and notes==\n;References\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite book |last=Ashton |first=Thomas Southcliffe |last2=Sykes |first2=Joseph |title=The Coal Industry of the Eighteenth Century |year=1929 |publisher=Manchester University Press |location=Manchester |oclc=3634819 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Day |first=Lance |last2=McNeil |first2=Ian |title=Biographical Dictionary of the History of Technology |year=1996 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |isbn=0-415-06042-7 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780415060424 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Galloway |first=Robert Lindsay |title=Annals of Coal Mining and the Coal Trade: The invention of the steam engine and the origin of the railway |year=1898 |publisher=The Colliery Guardian Company, Limited |location=London |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first=R.A. |last=Mott|title=Tramroads of the eighteenth century and their originator: John Curr|work=Transactions of the Newcomen Society|volume= XLII |year=1969\u201370|pages= 1\u201323|ref={{harvid|Mott|1969}}}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Medlicott |first=Ian R. |title=John Curr and the Development of the Sheffield Collieries, 1781\u20131805 |journal=Transactions of the Hunter Archaeological Society |year=1983 |volume=12 |page=51 |ref=harv}}\n*Alexander Lock, ''Catholicism, Identity and Politics in the Age of Enlightenment: The Life and Career of Sir Thomas Gascoigne, 1745\u20131810'' (Woodbridge: Boydell and Brewer, 2016), ch. 5\n*Alexander Lock, \u2018Curr, John (1756\u20131823)\u2019, ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, September 2015)\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Curr, John}}\n[[Category:1756 births]]\n[[Category:1823 deaths]]\n[[Category:British people in rail transport]]\n[[Category:British railway pioneers]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Yorkshire\u200e]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Sheffield\u200e]]\n[[Category:People of the Industrial Revolution]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n'''John Curr''' (c. 1756 \u2013 27 January 1823) was the manager or [[colliery viewer|viewer]] of the [[Duke of Norfolk]]'s [[collieries]] in [[Sheffield]], England from 1781 to 1801. During this time he made a number of innovations that contributed significantly to the development of the coal mining industry and railways.<ref>Alexander Lock, 'Curr, John (1756\u20131823)', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, Sep. 2015)</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCurr was born in [[County Durham]], England in around 1756.<ref name=\"Day184\">{{Harvnb|Day|McNeil|1996|p=184}}</ref> He was raised and remained a Catholic throughout his life. He moved to Sheffield some time before 1776. In 1780 he was appointed superintendent of the Duke of Norfolk's Sheffield collieries.<ref name=\"Day184\" /> He married Hannah Wilson (18 May 1759 \u2013 10 June 1851<ref>{{cite book|title=Miscellanea IV|year=1907|publisher=Catholic Record Society|page=366}}</ref>) in about 1785, and they had eight children, including [[Joseph Curr]], a Catholic priest, and [[Edward Curr]], who was Secretary of the [[Van Diemen's Land Company]] from 1824 to 1841. He died in Sheffield on 27 January 1823.<ref>{{cite news|title=Births, Deaths, Marriages and Obituaries|newspaper=The Bury and Norwich Post|date=5 February 1823}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nThe career of John Curr has been subject to significant dispute, due to inaccurate statements by early authors about him and misinterpretation.<ref>The historiography of the subject is dealt with at {{Harvnb|Mott|1969|pp=15\u201317 20\u201323}} and {{Harvnb|Lewis|1970|pp= 316\u20139}}.</ref> Older works (such as (or those quoting them) often give the date of his colliery inventions as 1776.<ref>{{Harvnb|Galloway|1898|pp=322\u20134}}</ref> Curr probably came to Sheffield in 1778.  That August, shortly before the expiry of the lease of Sheffield colliery (in Sheffield Park), he wrote a report on it for [[Charles Howard, 10th Duke of Norfolk|the Duke of Norfolk]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Mott|1969|pp=3}}: citing Sheffield Archives, ACM/S217.</ref> Contrary to statements by his son, he was probably not there in 1774, when there were riots against the colliery lessees, who insisted on selling coal only at a yard in Sheffield.<ref>''Universal Magazine'', 2 December 1774: reprinted {{Harvnb|Mott|1969|pp= 16}}.</ref> From Michaelmas 1779, he became superintendent of the Duke's Coal Works.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mott|1969|p= 4}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1787, [[John Buddle, senior]] reported on the transport system introduced by Curr.  He reported Curr's method using L-shaped [[cast iron]] plates cost 6\u00bcd per waggon, whereas the old method cost 10\u00bdd per waggon, a saving of 3\u00bed.  He also referred to Mr Curr's method of 'drawing 2 corves abreast up a shaft 8\u00bd to 9-foot diameter by means of steadying conductors'.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mott|1969|pp= 5}}, citing Sheffield Archives, ACMS223.</ref> Curr substituted small four-wheeled carriages for the sledges that had previously been used to transport coal underground,<ref>{{Harvnb|Galloway|1898|p=322}}</ref> but this meant that underground haulage by boys, rather than ponies.<ref>{{Harvnb|Lewis|1970|p=319}}</ref> The corf wheels and 'roadplates' came from Binks, Booth, and Hartop's nearby Park Ironworks.<ref>{{Harvnb|Lewis|1970|p= 318}} Identification of ironworks from C. Ball et al., ''Water Power on Sheffield Rivers'' (2nd edn, [[South Yorkshire Industrial History Society]], Sheffield, 2006), 192</ref>\n\nThe use of these rails was subsequently promoted by [[Benjamin Outram]] and adopted at many other English mines,<ref name=\"Day184\" /> quarries and ironworks.  In south Wales, railways using his system were known as tramroads (or dramroads).  Today, the term [[plateway]] is sometimes applied to them.\n\n==Patents==\n{|Class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year!!Number!!Subject\n|-\n|1788||1660||For raising coals out of mines using \"conductors\" with tiplers at the surface\n|-\n|1792||1924||For using double ropes\n|-\n|1798||1924||For using flat ropes wound in coils on the winding drum<ref>Mott, 6.</ref>\n|1813|3711|Applying flat ropes to horse-gins\n|-\n| || ||{{Expand list|date=January 2012}}\n|}\n\n== Publications ==\n*{{cite book |last=Curr |first=John |title=The Coal Viewer, and Engine Builder's Practical Companion |year=1797 |publisher=John Northall |location=Sheffield |oclc= 637327681 |ref=harv}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Edward Micklethwaite Curr]], John Curr's grandson\n\n==References and notes==\n;References\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite book |last=Ashton |first=Thomas Southcliffe |last2=Sykes |first2=Joseph |title=The Coal Industry of the Eighteenth Century |year=1929 |publisher=Manchester University Press |location=Manchester |oclc=3634819 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Day |first=Lance |last2=McNeil |first2=Ian |title=Biographical Dictionary of the History of Technology |year=1996 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |isbn=0-415-06042-7 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780415060424 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Galloway |first=Robert Lindsay |title=Annals of Coal Mining and the Coal Trade: The invention of the steam engine and the origin of the railway |year=1898 |publisher=The Colliery Guardian Company, Limited |location=London |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first=R.A. |last=Mott|title=Tramroads of the eighteenth century and their originator: John Curr|work=Transactions of the Newcomen Society|volume= XLII |year=1969\u201370|pages= 1\u201323|ref={{harvid|Mott|1969}}}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Medlicott |first=Ian R. |title=John Curr and the Development of the Sheffield Collieries, 1781\u20131805 |journal=Transactions of the Hunter Archaeological Society |year=1983 |volume=12 |page=51 |ref=harv}}\n*Alexander Lock, ''Catholicism, Identity and Politics in the Age of Enlightenment: The Life and Career of Sir Thomas Gascoigne, 1745\u20131810'' (Woodbridge: Boydell and Brewer, 2016), ch. 5\n*Alexander Lock, \u2018Curr, John (1756\u20131823)\u2019, ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, Sep. 2015)\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Curr, John}}\n[[Category:1756 births]]\n[[Category:1823 deaths]]\n[[Category:British people in rail transport]]\n[[Category:British railway pioneers]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Yorkshire\u200e]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Sheffield\u200e]]\n[[Category:People of the Industrial Revolution]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sep. -> September", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Curr"}
