nts of Axisymmetric Electrovacuum Spacetimes | journal=Class. Quantum Grav. | volume=21 | date=2004 | pages=5727\u20135733 | doi=10.1088/0264-9381/21/24/003 | arxiv=gr-qc/0407064 | bibcode=2004CQGra..21.5727S | issue=24}} Gives the relativistic multipole moments for the Ernst vacuums (plus the electromagnetic and gravitational relativistic multipole moments  for the charged generalization).\n*{{cite journal | last=Carter | first=B. | authorlink = Brandon Carter | date = 1971 | title = Axisymmetric Black Hole Has Only Two Degrees of Freedom | journal = Physical Review Letters | volume = 26 | pages = 331\u2013333 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.26.331 | bibcode=1971PhRvL..26..331C | issue = 6}}\n*{{cite book | last = Wald | first = R. M. | authorlink = Robert Wald | date = 1984 | title = General Relativity | url = https://archive.org/details/generalrelativit0000wald | url-access = registration | publisher = The University of Chicago Press | location = Chicago | isbn = 978-0-226-87032-8 | pages = 312&ndash;324}}\n*{{cite journal |author1=Kerr, R. P. |author2=Schild, A. |date=2009 |title= Republication of: A new class of vacuum solutions of the Einstein field equations |journal=General Relativity and Gravitation |volume=41 |pages=2485\u20132499 |doi=10.1007/s10714-009-0857-z |issue=10|bibcode = 2009GReGr..41.2485K }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Krasi\u0144ski |first1=Andrzej |last2=Verdaguer |first2=Enric |last3=Kerr |first3=Roy Patrick | date=2009 | title= Editorial note to: R. P. Kerr and A. Schild, A new class of vacuum solutions of the Einstein field equations |journal=General Relativity and Gravitation |volume=41 |pages=2469\u20132484 |doi=10.1007/s10714-009-0856-0 |issue=10 |bibcode = 2009GReGr..41.2469K }} \"\u2026 This note is meant to be a guide for those readers who wish to verify all the details [of the derivation of the Kerr solution]\u2026\"\n\n{{Black holes}}\n{{Time travel}}\n{{Relativity}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kerr Metric}}\n[[Category:Exact solutions in general relativity]]\n[[Category:Black holes]]\n[[Category:Metric tensors]]\n\n[[fr:Trou noir de Kerr#M\u00e9trique de Kerr]]\n", "name_user": "Jonesey95", "label": "safe", "comment": "FixLintererrors usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kerr_metric"}
{"title_page": "Provinces and territories of Canada", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Canadian Province|\"Canadian Province\" as used in biology|Circumboreal Region}}\n{{short description|Top-level subdivisions of Canada}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox subdivision type\n| name=Provinces and territories of Canada\n| map=AmelitaMelicor[[File:Political map of Canada.png|350px|A map of Canada showing its 10 provinces and 3 territories]]\n| category=[[Federated state]]\n| current_number=10 provinces<br />3 territories\n| number_date=\n| population_range=\n| area_range=\n| government= \n| subdivision=\n}}\n\nThe '''provinces and territories of Canada''' are sub-national divisions within the geographical areas of [[Canada]] under the jurisdiction of the [[Constitution of Canada|Canadian Constitution]]. In the 1867 [[Canadian Confederation]], three provinces of [[British North America]]\u2014[[New Brunswick]], [[Nova Scotia]], and the [[Province of Canada]] (which upon Confederation was divided into [[Ontario]] and [[Quebec]])\u2014were united to form a federated colony, becoming a sovereign nation in the next century. Over its history, Canada's international borders have changed several times, and the country has grown from the original four provinces to the current ten provinces and three territories. Together, the provinces and territories make up the [[List of countries and dependencies by area|world's second-largest country]] by area.\n\nThe major difference between a Canadian province and a [[territory]] is that provinces receive their power and authority from the ''[[Constitution Act, 1867]]'' (formerly<ref>Name changed only in Canada by <i>Canada Act, 1982</i> (UK), s. 1--see Talk</ref> called ''[[British North America Acts|The British North America Act, 1867]]''), whereas territorial governments have powers delegated to them by the [[Parliament of Canada]]. The powers flowing from the ''Constitution Act'' are divided between the [[Government of Canada]] (the federal government) and the provincial governments to exercise exclusively. A change to the division of powers between the federal government and the provinces requires a [[Amendments to the Constitution of Canada|constitutional amendment]], whereas a similar change affecting the territories can be performed unilaterally by the Parliament of Canada or government.\n\nIn modern [[Canadian federalism|Canadian constitutional theory]], the provinces are considered [[sovereignty|sovereign]] within certain areas based on the divisions of responsibility between the provincial and federal government within the ''Constitution Act 1867'', and each province thus has its own representative of the Canadian \"[[monarchy in the Canadian provinces|Crown]]\", the [[Lieutenant governor (Canada)|lieutenant governor]]. The territories are not sovereign, but instead their authorities and responsibilities come directly from the federal level, and as a result, have a commissioner instead of a lieutenant governor.\n__TOC__\n\n==Provinces==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\" rowspan=\"2\" | Arms\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Province\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Canadian postal abbreviations for provinces and territories|Postal<br/>abbrev.]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Capital<br/><ref name=\"canada1\"/>\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Largest<br />city<ref>{{cite web |author=Place name |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/index.cfm?Lang=E |title=Census Profile |publisher=Statistic Canada |year=2013 |accessdate=August 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208074653/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/index.cfm?Lang=E |archive-date=February 8, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Entered<br />Confederation<ref name=\"(Canada)2004\">{{cite book|author=Reader's Digest Association (Canada)|author2=Canadian Geographic Enterprises|title=The Canadian Atlas: Our Nation, Environment and People|url=https: